So heres the deal: MSRF logs are often disguised under totally different sheet names, and they usually follow these patterns:

Where MSRF data normally hides (your file likely has one of these):

1. Request Register, Service Request, or Material Request

Same thing, new name.
MSRF = Material/Service Request Form.

2. Indent List or Indent Register

Old-school procurement term.
Indent = request before PO.
Many companies use this instead of MSRF.

3. Requisition Register, Req Log, Req Tracker, Job Request

Still MSRF, just with a different coat of paint.

4. Procurement Log, PR Log, MR Log

Companies often merge all MSRFs into the PR/MR sheet.

5. Hidden inside PO Log but with an MSRF column

Some teams skip a separate MSRF log.
They just track MSRF ID, PO number, status all in one combined table.

6. A Master Summary sheet that has MSRF columns

Sometimes the granular MSRF entries are inside one big combined table.

How to identify it instantly

Look for any sheet containing columns like:

  • Request ID

  • Priority

  • Category / Item Type

  • Department

  • Request Date

  • Status (Pending, Revised, Approved, etc.)

If you see Priority or Immediate / P1 / P2, congrats, that's your MSRF log.

Your dashboards ONLY show MSRF data for 3 months:

  • October

  • MSRF is kept separately
